1. Understanding the Concepts
Kendall's Notation (A/S/c/N/D)

A (Arrival times): How frequently entities arrive. M means Markovian (Exponential distribution), D means Deterministic (constant time), G means General.
S (Service times): How long it takes to process an entity. Follows the same letters as A.
c (Servers): The number of parallel servers processing entities.
N (Capacity): The maximum number of entities allowed in the system (queue + inside service). If a new entity arrives when full, it is dropped.
D (Discipline): Order of processing (e.g., FIFO = First-In-First-Out, LIFO = Last-In-First-Out).
Event-Driven Architecture (Event Scheduling) Instead of advancing simulation time step-by-step (e.g., tick by tick), we jump directly to the time when the next event happens. We maintain an "Event Calendar" (a priority queue ordered by time). The two main events in a basic queue are:

Arrival: An entity enters the system. We schedule the next arrival and handle the current entity setup (either goes into service or a waiting queue).
Departure: An entity finishes service. We free up the server. If there's anyone waiting in the queue, they immediately begin service.
Modularity
To connect queues, a Departure from Queue 1 can simply trigger an Arrival into Queue 2 instead of leaving the system completely.

